Persistent mounts — etc-fstab and UUID.

A mount you do by hand with the mount command is temporary; it's gone the moment you reboot. To make a mount persistent, so it comes back automatically every boot, you add an entry to the file etc-fstab, the filesystems table. Each line in fstab has six space-separated fields, so let's walk them.

Field one is the device: what to mount. And you should strongly prefer a UUID here, which we'll get to in a moment. Field two is the mount point, where to attach it, and it must already exist; for swap you write none. Field three is the type: ext4, xfs, swap, tmpfs, and so on, or auto to let the kernel guess. Field four is the options, comma-separated, the same ones from the mounting section; defaults for normal use, or just sw for swap. Field five is the dump field, used by an ancient backup tool; today you always set it to zero. And field six is the pass field, which sets the order of the boot-time fsck: one for the root filesystem, two for other filesystems, and zero for "don't check," which you use for swap and network filesystems.

Now, why UUID? Because, as we saw, device names like slash-dev-sdb-one can change between boots. A UUID, by contrast, is a globally unique identifier assigned to a filesystem when it's created, and it never changes, even if the device gets renamed. You can see the UUIDs with the blkid command, or with lsblk dash-f. So in fstab you write UUID-equals and the value, rather than a device path. A label, set with dash-capital-L at format time, is a friendlier alternative you can also use. The rule to remember: raw device names should not appear in a production fstab.

And finally, the safety habit that saves careers. After editing fstab, test it before you reboot, because a broken fstab can drop the machine into emergency mode at the next boot, and now you're at a rescue console. So run sudo mount dash-a, which mounts everything in fstab that isn't already mounted, and findmnt dash-dash-verify, which validates the syntax. The safe pattern for a new entry is: mount it manually first to confirm it works, then unmount, then add the fstab line, then run mount dash-a to test that the fstab entry itself is correct, and only then trust it across a reboot.
